00:00:02.470 --> 00:00:04.446 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.446 --> 00:00:07.410 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:10.097 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.097 --> 00:00:12.680 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So this here is
just to make sure that you are

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:28.440 align:middle line:84%
in the right place, which
is 18.100B or 18.1002.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:31.430 align:middle line:84%
And my name is Toby,
so Toby Colding.

00:00:31.430 --> 00:00:36.560 align:middle line:90%


00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:40.440 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, so
we will be recorded.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:46.160 align:middle line:84%
And the video from the
lecture will be posted online.

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:49.700 align:middle line:84%
And I will also
write lecture notes.

00:00:49.700 --> 00:00:53.140 align:middle line:84%
I hope you appreciate it
because I wrote the first one.

00:00:53.140 --> 00:00:54.920 align:middle line:84%
It actually took me
quite a long time.

00:00:54.920 --> 00:00:58.060 align:middle line:84%
I don't typically type
the lecture notes,

00:00:58.060 --> 00:01:01.340 align:middle line:84%
but I will do this
for this class.

00:01:01.340 --> 00:01:06.800 align:middle line:84%
And I also wanted to just give
you an idea of the structure.

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:09.580 align:middle line:84%
First of all, this is one
of the most important math

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:12.620 align:middle line:90%
classes at MIT.

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:16.660 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you in a
minute why it is important.

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:18.660 align:middle line:84%
And of course, I
think that, being

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:20.340 align:middle line:84%
one of the most
important math classes,

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.600 align:middle line:84%
it's one of the most
important classes, period.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.940 align:middle line:90%


00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:30.500 align:middle line:84%
But just to give you
an idea of what will

00:01:30.500 --> 00:01:32.300 align:middle line:90%
be expected from the class--

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:34.950 align:middle line:84%
so there will be
10 weekly homework.

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:39.980 align:middle line:90%


00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:47.100 align:middle line:84%
And the first one, it
won't be due next week.

00:01:47.100 --> 00:01:51.340 align:middle line:84%
It will probably be due
the week after next week.

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:56.180 align:middle line:84%
And in part, it will just allow
you to get settled in a bit.

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:59.920 align:middle line:84%
But also, I'm waiting
for somebody else

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:02.300 align:middle line:90%
to assign the TA and the grader.

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.600 align:middle line:84%
So I think it will be at
least one graduate TA,

00:02:05.600 --> 00:02:10.960 align:middle line:84%
and there will be some
undergraduate TAs.

00:02:10.960 --> 00:02:14.320 align:middle line:84%
And then there will also
probably be some graders.

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:18.020 align:middle line:84%
And most of these,
including myself,

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:20.480 align:middle line:90%
will have office hours or so.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.720 align:middle line:90%
So it'll be 10 weekly homework.

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:34.480 align:middle line:84%
There will be a midterm, so
one midterm and one final.

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:38.840 align:middle line:90%
And the midterm is on March 20.

00:02:38.840 --> 00:02:42.400 align:middle line:90%
And the final is--

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:43.860 align:middle line:90%
I don't know when it is.

00:02:43.860 --> 00:02:48.520 align:middle line:84%
I'm not the one that
is deciding the date.

00:02:48.520 --> 00:02:53.200 align:middle line:84%
And it will be a while before
we know what date that will be.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:57.940 align:middle line:84%
And in terms of the
grade, the homework

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:01.380 align:middle line:84%
will count for
50% of your grade,

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:06.820 align:middle line:84%
midterm will count for
20%, and the final for 30%

00:03:06.820 --> 00:03:11.420 align:middle line:84%
And you can see all this
information about this in--

00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:13.740 align:middle line:84%
there's a syllabus and
a course information

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:16.340 align:middle line:90%
posted on the Canvas.

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:23.260 align:middle line:84%
So make sure to check out the
Canvas site for the class.

00:03:23.260 --> 00:03:26.300 align:middle line:84%
And there's also the
information about the book.

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:30.660 align:middle line:84%
And also, the lecture notes will
be posted on the Canvas site.

00:03:30.660 --> 00:03:34.320 align:middle line:84%
The lecture notes, I think, will
probably be posted on the files.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:41.310 align:middle line:84%
So lecture notes will
be posted on the files.

00:03:41.310 --> 00:03:54.200 align:middle line:90%


00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:59.040 align:middle line:84%
And one other thing is
that I have activated

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:00.470 align:middle line:90%
what's called pset partners.

00:04:00.470 --> 00:04:06.200 align:middle line:90%


00:04:06.200 --> 00:04:12.100 align:middle line:84%
So you are encouraged to work
with other people on the psets,

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:15.400 align:middle line:84%
but everybody have to
hand in their own psets.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:21.800 align:middle line:84%
And pset partners is a way
of finding other people

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:23.180 align:middle line:90%
to work with.

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:25.260 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you can
do it another way.

00:04:25.260 --> 00:04:29.130 align:middle line:84%
But this is a tool that is
used in a lot of classes.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.460 align:middle line:90%


00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:31.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:36.920 align:middle line:84%
I think this covered
the basic information.

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:39.080 align:middle line:90%
And so the class here is--

00:04:39.080 --> 00:04:44.480 align:middle line:84%
so the two key topics
for this class is--

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:54.820 align:middle line:84%
so key topics, one
is you will learn how

00:04:54.820 --> 00:04:59.150 align:middle line:90%
to write a mathematical proof.

00:04:59.150 --> 00:05:05.060 align:middle line:90%


00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:09.080 align:middle line:84%
So what does it mean
to write something

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:12.380 align:middle line:84%
so that is
mathematically rigorous?

00:05:12.380 --> 00:05:14.220 align:middle line:84%
And the second thing
that you will learn

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:15.630 align:middle line:90%
is how to prove theorems.

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:25.820 align:middle line:90%


00:05:25.820 --> 00:05:29.940 align:middle line:84%
And so here's an
example of this.

00:05:29.940 --> 00:05:32.660 align:middle line:84%
Let's suppose you
have a function.

00:05:32.660 --> 00:05:34.440 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you
have some interval.

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:38.380 align:middle line:90%
So a and b are real numbers.

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:44.740 align:middle line:84%
And you have a function f
defined on this interval.

00:05:44.740 --> 00:05:47.140 align:middle line:90%
And you take real values.

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.800 align:middle line:84%
And so here, you have
the interval here, a.

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:52.480 align:middle line:90%
Here's b.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:58.620 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that the
value at a is negative,

00:05:58.620 --> 00:06:03.600 align:middle line:84%
and the value at the other
endpoint, b, is positive.

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:08.280 align:middle line:84%
So if you were drawing the
graph, here, you have a, maybe.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:09.920 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have b.

00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:13.160 align:middle line:84%
And then the function
initially is negative,

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:15.300 align:middle line:90%
and it end up being positive.

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:17.360 align:middle line:90%
So this is f of a.

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:20.840 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have f of b.

00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:23.420 align:middle line:84%
And then this function
here is continuous.

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:28.440 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:31.100 align:middle line:84%
So the function looks
maybe like this.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:34.840 align:middle line:90%


00:06:34.840 --> 00:06:36.500 align:middle line:90%
So f is continuous.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:39.050 align:middle line:84%
So the intermediate
value theorem's saying--

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:54.850 align:middle line:90%


00:06:54.850 --> 00:06:56.780 align:middle line:84%
so the intermediate
value theorem.

00:06:56.780 --> 00:07:09.867 align:middle line:90%


00:07:09.867 --> 00:07:11.450 align:middle line:84%
It's saying the
following, that if you

00:07:11.450 --> 00:07:15.130 align:middle line:84%
have a continuous function
on an interval, then

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:18.650 align:middle line:90%
it takes all values in between.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.570 align:middle line:84%
So the intermediate value
theorem says in particular

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:27.810 align:middle line:90%
that there exists a c.

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:32.930 align:middle line:84%
And the c here is
between a and b

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:38.190 align:middle line:84%
so that the value of
the function at c is 0.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:42.330 align:middle line:84%
Because the function starts off
negative, and it end positive.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:45.810 align:middle line:84%
So there must be somewhere
in between where it hits 0.

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:49.150 align:middle line:84%
That's the intermediate
value theorem.

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:55.390 align:middle line:84%
But now the question is then,
how do we make this into--

00:07:55.390 --> 00:07:57.470 align:middle line:90%
and it's kind of obvious.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:08:04.790 align:middle line:84%
It's sort of intuitively obvious
that if you take a function,

00:08:04.790 --> 00:08:08.590 align:middle line:84%
continuous means something
like that if you were drawing

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:13.550 align:middle line:84%
the graph, and you'd have
this piece of chalk here,

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:17.110 align:middle line:84%
then as you're
drawing the graph,

00:08:17.110 --> 00:08:20.690 align:middle line:84%
the chalk is not allowed
to leave your table.

00:08:20.690 --> 00:08:24.030 align:middle line:84%
It can't have a
function like this here

00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:28.210 align:middle line:84%
that jumps, so go like this,
and then jumps like this.

00:08:28.210 --> 00:08:30.330 align:middle line:90%
That's not continuous.

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:34.030 align:middle line:90%
This is not continuous.

00:08:34.030 --> 00:08:38.730 align:middle line:84%
So continuous function is that
you have to, when you draw it,

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:40.470 align:middle line:90%
it's in one motion.

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:44.130 align:middle line:84%
The chalk doesn't
leave the blackboard.

00:08:44.130 --> 00:08:47.490 align:middle line:84%
And so it seems
obvious that there

00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:51.130 align:middle line:84%
should be some point
in between where

00:08:51.130 --> 00:08:53.530 align:middle line:90%
you're crossing this axis here.

00:08:53.530 --> 00:08:56.070 align:middle line:84%
But how do we make this
into a rigorous proof?

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:58.510 align:middle line:90%
And what is the property?

00:08:58.510 --> 00:09:00.440 align:middle line:84%
So how do we make
this into a proof?

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:04.290 align:middle line:90%


00:09:04.290 --> 00:09:20.950 align:middle line:84%
So how do we make this
intuition into a proof?

00:09:20.950 --> 00:09:25.210 align:middle line:90%


00:09:25.210 --> 00:09:29.350 align:middle line:84%
And this is not just
a semantic question.

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:32.450 align:middle line:90%
It's not just a crazy question.

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:35.730 align:middle line:84%
Maybe in this case,
it seemed clear.

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:39.850 align:middle line:84%
But very quickly, if
your foundation is not

00:09:39.850 --> 00:09:43.110 align:middle line:84%
totally rigorous, then
you get into something

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:47.510 align:middle line:84%
where it seems to be the case,
but it might not be the case.

00:09:47.510 --> 00:09:50.910 align:middle line:84%
And it's also very
difficult to then--

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:52.590 align:middle line:84%
quickly, that's
where you arrive.

00:09:52.590 --> 00:09:54.690 align:middle line:84%
And you also quickly
arrive to that

00:09:54.690 --> 00:09:59.090 align:middle line:84%
you don't even know whether
it should be the case or not.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:03.610 align:middle line:84%
And so it's really important to
build things up, step to step,

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:06.310 align:middle line:84%
where each step is
totally rigorous.

00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:10.930 align:middle line:84%
And you write it
because it's not only

00:10:10.930 --> 00:10:13.850 align:middle line:84%
you know for sure
that things are right,

00:10:13.850 --> 00:10:18.830 align:middle line:84%
but it also makes it much easier
to predict what should be true.

00:10:18.830 --> 00:10:24.150 align:middle line:84%
And so in order
to understand why

00:10:24.150 --> 00:10:30.230 align:middle line:84%
there should be some
c between a and b

00:10:30.230 --> 00:10:36.190 align:middle line:84%
where the value is 0,
immediately, the first question

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:37.550 align:middle line:90%
that arises--

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:38.730 align:middle line:90%
what are you using?

00:10:38.730 --> 00:10:43.110 align:middle line:84%
What property do we need
to make this into a proof?

00:10:43.110 --> 00:10:45.970 align:middle line:84%
What property do we need
of the real numbers?

00:10:45.970 --> 00:10:49.830 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
question that arises.

00:10:49.830 --> 00:11:05.940 align:middle line:84%
So what property are we
using of the real numbers?

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:12.810 align:middle line:90%


00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:18.050 align:middle line:84%
And so, in fact, what
is the real numbers?

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:19.640 align:middle line:90%
So what are the real numbers?

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:33.770 align:middle line:90%


00:11:33.770 --> 00:11:41.098 align:middle line:84%
And so the thing is
that, in particular,

00:11:41.098 --> 00:11:43.990 align:middle line:90%
what is square root of 2?

00:11:43.990 --> 00:11:45.690 align:middle line:90%
So what is square root of 2?

00:11:45.690 --> 00:11:54.040 align:middle line:90%


00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:55.520 align:middle line:90%
And is that a real number?

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:58.270 align:middle line:90%


00:11:58.270 --> 00:12:00.850 align:middle line:84%
Is square root of
2 a real number?

00:12:00.850 --> 00:12:13.070 align:middle line:90%


00:12:13.070 --> 00:12:15.870 align:middle line:84%
So those are some
of the questions

00:12:15.870 --> 00:12:19.670 align:middle line:90%
that you immediately get to.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:24.910 align:middle line:84%
And so now-- but so
the answer to, what

00:12:24.910 --> 00:12:27.730 align:middle line:84%
are the properties that you're
using of the real numbers?

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:33.810 align:middle line:84%
So the answer to this question
here is the following.

00:12:33.810 --> 00:12:43.050 align:middle line:90%


00:12:43.050 --> 00:12:45.110 align:middle line:84%
So the answer to
this question is--

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:50.130 align:middle line:84%
so what are the property of the
real numbers that you're using?

00:12:50.130 --> 00:12:59.850 align:middle line:84%
So the answer to that
is the following,

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:17.322 align:middle line:84%
that the real numbers-- so R
is a complete ordered field

00:13:17.322 --> 00:13:39.430 align:middle line:84%
that contains the rational
numbers, the rational numbers,

00:13:39.430 --> 00:13:40.430 align:middle line:90%
Q.

00:13:40.430 --> 00:13:43.790 align:middle line:84%
I denote the rational numbers
by Q and the real numbers

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:54.110 align:middle line:84%
by capital R. So in order to
make this the intermediate value

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:58.670 align:middle line:84%
theorem, this property that
if you have an integral from a

00:13:58.670 --> 00:14:02.290 align:middle line:84%
to b, you have a continuous
function on that interval.

00:14:02.290 --> 00:14:04.390 align:middle line:84%
And it starts off
negative, and it

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:07.830 align:middle line:84%
ends positive-- that then
there is some value in between,

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:09.130 align:middle line:90%
where 0 is achieved.

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:12.390 align:middle line:84%
In order to make that
rigorous, what you're

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:15.230 align:middle line:84%
using about the real numbers
is that it's complete

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:18.430 align:middle line:84%
ordered field that contains
irrational numbers.

00:14:18.430 --> 00:14:21.430 align:middle line:84%
So we need to understand
what this here means.

00:14:21.430 --> 00:14:27.070 align:middle line:84%
And in this lecture here, I
will not explain complete.

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:29.430 align:middle line:84%
I will do that at
a later lecture.

00:14:29.430 --> 00:14:35.050 align:middle line:84%
But we will understand the rest
of what are these properties

00:14:35.050 --> 00:14:36.570 align:middle line:90%
that we're using.

00:14:36.570 --> 00:14:38.470 align:middle line:90%
So just first, some notation--

00:14:38.470 --> 00:14:56.570 align:middle line:90%


00:14:56.570 --> 00:15:00.890 align:middle line:84%
so the natural numbers
here, this here

00:15:00.890 --> 00:15:08.610 align:middle line:90%
is 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, et cetera.

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:10.220 align:middle line:84%
So these are the
natural numbers.

00:15:10.220 --> 00:15:21.050 align:middle line:90%


00:15:21.050 --> 00:15:27.340 align:middle line:84%
The integers-- so 2 set
here, these are the integers.

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:31.590 align:middle line:90%


00:15:31.590 --> 00:15:36.490 align:middle line:84%
And the integers are
simply the natural numbers.

00:15:36.490 --> 00:15:39.910 align:middle line:84%
But then it also allows
them to be negative,

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:41.910 align:middle line:90%
and it also includes 0.

00:15:41.910 --> 00:15:47.710 align:middle line:84%
So this is 0 plus or
minus 1, plus or minus 2,

00:15:47.710 --> 00:15:51.430 align:middle line:90%
plus or minus 3, et cetera.

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.110 align:middle line:90%
These are the integers.

00:15:54.110 --> 00:16:05.230 align:middle line:84%
The rational numbers are then--
so the rational numbers, Q,

00:16:05.230 --> 00:16:10.810 align:middle line:84%
so these are numbers
of the form m/n,

00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:17.550 align:middle line:84%
where m here is an
integer and n here--

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:18.400 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:22.230 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, m is an integer, and
n here is a natural number.

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:24.830 align:middle line:90%


00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:27.950 align:middle line:90%
That's a rational number.

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:32.490 align:middle line:84%
And so now what
are the properties?

00:16:32.490 --> 00:16:36.090 align:middle line:84%
So we're building up to trying
to understand what property

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:37.530 align:middle line:90%
of the real numbers is.

00:16:37.530 --> 00:16:42.370 align:middle line:84%
But let's try to somehow
understand it a bit better.

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:44.610 align:middle line:84%
What are the properties
that we really have

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:47.810 align:middle line:90%
about the rational numbers?

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:51.370 align:middle line:84%
So for rational
numbers, we have--

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:56.956 align:middle line:84%
so we write a rational number
as a quotient, like that.

00:16:56.956 --> 00:16:59.050 align:middle line:84%
But of course,
there are many ways

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:01.370 align:middle line:90%
that you can write a quotient.

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:04.040 align:middle line:84%
So properties of the
rational numbers--

00:17:04.040 --> 00:17:16.609 align:middle line:90%


00:17:16.609 --> 00:17:21.569 align:middle line:84%
so we write it as a
quotient, like this.

00:17:21.569 --> 00:17:26.290 align:middle line:84%
But this is not
uniquely defined.

00:17:26.290 --> 00:17:29.670 align:middle line:84%
If you take a
quotient, like this,

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:35.875 align:middle line:84%
you think that this here is
equal to another quotient,

00:17:35.875 --> 00:17:38.430 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:47.390 align:middle line:84%
Again, m1 and m2 are
integers, and n1 and n2

00:17:47.390 --> 00:17:50.110 align:middle line:90%
are natural numbers.

00:17:50.110 --> 00:17:53.830 align:middle line:84%
Two quotients are
the same if and only

00:17:53.830 --> 00:18:00.310 align:middle line:84%
if that if you multiply this
over here and this over there,

00:18:00.310 --> 00:18:02.970 align:middle line:90%
then those numbers are the same.

00:18:02.970 --> 00:18:11.670 align:middle line:84%
So n2 times N2 is
equal to N2 times n1.

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:15.030 align:middle line:84%
Those two rational
numbers are the same if

00:18:15.030 --> 00:18:19.230 align:middle line:84%
and only if those two natural
numbers are the same--

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:23.176 align:middle line:84%
or integers, because
m could be negative.

00:18:23.176 --> 00:18:27.050 align:middle line:90%


00:18:27.050 --> 00:18:33.450 align:middle line:84%
So again, a rational number, it
has a representative like this.

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:37.130 align:middle line:84%
But you could think
about it as always, you

00:18:37.130 --> 00:18:39.270 align:middle line:90%
can write this quotient.

00:18:39.270 --> 00:18:41.970 align:middle line:84%
And two quotients are
the same if and only

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:45.210 align:middle line:90%
if this here is the case.

00:18:45.210 --> 00:18:48.280 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means
to be a rational number.

00:18:48.280 --> 00:18:53.205 align:middle line:90%


00:18:53.205 --> 00:18:56.770 align:middle line:84%
But then there are
some operations.

00:18:56.770 --> 00:18:59.510 align:middle line:84%
If you have two
rational numbers,

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:02.200 align:middle line:84%
then you can add two
rational numbers together.

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:05.630 align:middle line:90%


00:19:05.630 --> 00:19:09.570 align:middle line:84%
And that's really important,
that you have some operations

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:12.370 align:middle line:90%
on the rational numbers.

00:19:12.370 --> 00:19:14.030 align:middle line:90%
So if you take--

00:19:14.030 --> 00:19:18.130 align:middle line:90%


00:19:18.130 --> 00:19:21.650 align:middle line:84%
this here is one
rational number.

00:19:21.650 --> 00:19:25.650 align:middle line:84%
And if you now take another
rational number, m2/n2--

00:19:25.650 --> 00:19:29.910 align:middle line:90%


00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:34.196 align:middle line:84%
then how do you add two
rational numbers together?

00:19:34.196 --> 00:19:36.750 align:middle line:84%
Well, of course, you
know that you put it

00:19:36.750 --> 00:19:38.630 align:middle line:90%
on the common denominator.

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:49.430 align:middle line:84%
So this here is m1 times n2 plus
m2 times n1 divided by n1 times

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:52.270 align:middle line:90%
n2.

00:19:52.270 --> 00:19:55.310 align:middle line:84%
This here is an integer
in the denominator.

00:19:55.310 --> 00:19:58.970 align:middle line:84%
And this is a natural
number in the denominator.

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:03.990 align:middle line:84%
And so that's representative
of a rational number.

00:20:03.990 --> 00:20:06.950 align:middle line:90%
So that's an operation.

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:12.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, in order to really
know that this is--

00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:17.350 align:middle line:84%
so the idea here is that if
you take one rational number,

00:20:17.350 --> 00:20:20.910 align:middle line:84%
like this, and you take
another rational number,

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:25.240 align:middle line:84%
like that, then
you can add them.

00:20:25.240 --> 00:20:30.096 align:middle line:84%
And that gives you
another rational number.

00:20:30.096 --> 00:20:35.120 align:middle line:84%
That's this operation that we
know so well and its addition.

00:20:35.120 --> 00:20:38.240 align:middle line:90%


00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:41.440 align:middle line:84%
In order for this
really to make sense,

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:48.680 align:middle line:84%
you should check that this
rational number you get

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:52.200 align:middle line:84%
is independent on
the representation.

00:20:52.200 --> 00:20:54.680 align:middle line:84%
If you have another
representation

00:20:54.680 --> 00:20:59.240 align:middle line:84%
for the same rational number
and another representation

00:20:59.240 --> 00:21:02.560 align:middle line:84%
for the same rational number,
then when you add them,

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:04.920 align:middle line:84%
you should get
another representation

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:08.200 align:middle line:90%
for the same rational number.

00:21:08.200 --> 00:21:11.200 align:middle line:90%


00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:15.560 align:middle line:84%
And we will check one of
these things in just a minute.

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:19.710 align:middle line:90%
The other thing is that--

00:21:19.710 --> 00:21:22.740 align:middle line:90%


00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:24.580 align:middle line:90%
so that was one operation.

00:21:24.580 --> 00:21:27.580 align:middle line:84%
When you have the
rational number,

00:21:27.580 --> 00:21:30.620 align:middle line:90%
then addition is one operation.

00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:33.880 align:middle line:84%
Another operation is, of
course, multiplication.

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:37.260 align:middle line:90%


00:21:37.260 --> 00:21:39.760 align:middle line:84%
So another operation
is multiplication.

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:49.260 align:middle line:90%


00:21:49.260 --> 00:21:53.740 align:middle line:84%
And so if you take one
rational number, like this,

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:57.700 align:middle line:84%
and you take another
rational number,

00:21:57.700 --> 00:22:01.460 align:middle line:84%
like that, then if
you multiply them

00:22:01.460 --> 00:22:04.340 align:middle line:84%
together-- so what does
it mean to multiply

00:22:04.340 --> 00:22:06.540 align:middle line:90%
two rational number together?

00:22:06.540 --> 00:22:09.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, of course, you
know this very well.

00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:13.420 align:middle line:84%
It's just multiplying
the denominator.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:15.940 align:middle line:90%
So that gives you an integer.

00:22:15.940 --> 00:22:18.760 align:middle line:84%
And then multiplying
the denominator,

00:22:18.760 --> 00:22:20.260 align:middle line:90%
that gives you a natural number.

00:22:20.260 --> 00:22:22.060 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a
rational number.

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:25.600 align:middle line:90%


00:22:25.600 --> 00:22:29.180 align:middle line:90%
And then there's another thing.

00:22:29.180 --> 00:22:31.760 align:middle line:90%
So this is addition.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:32.900 align:middle line:90%
This was addition.

00:22:32.900 --> 00:22:34.880 align:middle line:90%
This is multiplication.

00:22:34.880 --> 00:22:38.600 align:middle line:84%
But there's another
important property

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:41.040 align:middle line:84%
that you have for
the rational number.

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:42.350 align:middle line:90%
And that is an ordering.

00:22:42.350 --> 00:22:46.640 align:middle line:90%


00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:48.920 align:middle line:84%
Again, we're trying to
understand this question

00:22:48.920 --> 00:22:49.700 align:middle line:90%
up there.

00:22:49.700 --> 00:22:52.360 align:middle line:84%
But we want to try to
understand, how do we

00:22:52.360 --> 00:22:55.660 align:middle line:84%
make the intermediate
value theorem--

00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:57.480 align:middle line:90%
how do we make this rigorous?

00:22:57.480 --> 00:22:59.800 align:middle line:84%
And so we need to
understand what property

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:03.360 align:middle line:90%
of the real numbers we need.

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:05.260 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
explained in this.

00:23:05.260 --> 00:23:08.080 align:middle line:84%
And we were working towards
trying to understand

00:23:08.080 --> 00:23:10.060 align:middle line:90%
the different concepts in this.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:10.940 align:middle line:90%
What is a field?

00:23:10.940 --> 00:23:13.960 align:middle line:84%
That's what we're
trying to understand.

00:23:13.960 --> 00:23:17.960 align:middle line:84%
And so we have addition
in the rational numbers.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:19.000 align:middle line:90%
We have addition.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:20.420 align:middle line:90%
We have multiplication.

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:24.900 align:middle line:84%
But we have another operation
on it, which is an ordering.

00:23:24.900 --> 00:23:31.340 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a
rational number here,

00:23:31.340 --> 00:23:34.380 align:middle line:84%
then you can say that this
rational number is less

00:23:34.380 --> 00:23:36.460 align:middle line:90%
than another rational number.

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:40.420 align:middle line:84%
When is it less than
another rational number,

00:23:40.420 --> 00:23:42.620 align:middle line:90%
this is equivalent to saying--

00:23:42.620 --> 00:23:46.680 align:middle line:84%
remember that these here
are natural numbers.

00:23:46.680 --> 00:23:48.140 align:middle line:90%
So they're positive.

00:23:48.140 --> 00:23:51.420 align:middle line:84%
So that this rational
number is less

00:23:51.420 --> 00:23:55.100 align:middle line:84%
than that just
means that m1 times

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:59.120 align:middle line:90%
n2 is less than m2 times n1.

00:23:59.120 --> 00:24:01.820 align:middle line:90%


00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:07.160 align:middle line:84%
Here, I am just multiplying
over here over here.

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:12.180 align:middle line:84%
And I'm using, of course, that
these numbers here are positive.

00:24:12.180 --> 00:24:12.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:12.860 --> 00:24:14.320 align:middle line:90%
So this is an ordering.

00:24:14.320 --> 00:24:18.740 align:middle line:84%
So in the rational numbers,
there is actually ordering.

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:21.660 align:middle line:90%
So that's really important also.

00:24:21.660 --> 00:24:24.860 align:middle line:84%
So we have these two operations,
and then we have an ordering.

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:31.460 align:middle line:90%


00:24:31.460 --> 00:24:34.180 align:middle line:84%
So here is-- so
let me just check.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:38.840 align:middle line:84%
So I said that when we
talked about addition, when

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:42.000 align:middle line:84%
we talk about addition here,
then there was something,

00:24:42.000 --> 00:24:46.620 align:middle line:84%
really, you had to check,
that this even made any sense.

00:24:46.620 --> 00:24:49.480 align:middle line:84%
And for this to
make any sense means

00:24:49.480 --> 00:24:54.720 align:middle line:84%
that this rational number
you get from adding these two

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:58.760 align:middle line:84%
is independent on how you
write this rational number

00:24:58.760 --> 00:25:01.080 align:middle line:84%
and how you write
that rational number--

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:04.960 align:middle line:90%
and the same for multiplication.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:07.030 align:middle line:90%
So let us check that.

00:25:07.030 --> 00:25:12.100 align:middle line:90%


00:25:12.100 --> 00:25:29.372 align:middle line:84%
So this here is checking
that multiplication

00:25:29.372 --> 00:25:46.860 align:middle line:84%
is a well-defined operation,
i.e, it is independent.

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:57.040 align:middle line:84%
It is independent of
the representative.

00:25:57.040 --> 00:26:04.220 align:middle line:90%


00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:09.440 align:middle line:84%
So we are multiplying-- we
take this rational number.

00:26:09.440 --> 00:26:11.920 align:middle line:84%
Sorry, let me write
a little bit bigger--

00:26:11.920 --> 00:26:13.840 align:middle line:90%
this rational number.

00:26:13.840 --> 00:26:17.480 align:middle line:90%
So this is one rational number.

00:26:17.480 --> 00:26:24.280 align:middle line:84%
And we multiply
this rational number

00:26:24.280 --> 00:26:26.300 align:middle line:90%
by another rational number.

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:29.690 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it p1 comma q1.

00:26:29.690 --> 00:26:33.280 align:middle line:90%


00:26:33.280 --> 00:26:35.800 align:middle line:84%
And then we take
another representative

00:26:35.800 --> 00:26:38.040 align:middle line:90%
for the same rational number.

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:39.500 align:middle line:90%
And let's call this m2/n2.

00:26:39.500 --> 00:26:42.840 align:middle line:90%


00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:46.780 align:middle line:84%
And for this rational number,
we take another representative.

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:51.040 align:middle line:90%


00:26:51.040 --> 00:26:56.240 align:middle line:84%
And we want to prove
that this number here is

00:26:56.240 --> 00:27:00.280 align:middle line:90%
the same as that number here.

00:27:00.280 --> 00:27:01.970 align:middle line:90%
So how do we do that?

00:27:01.970 --> 00:27:08.560 align:middle line:90%


00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:13.920 align:middle line:84%
So we have that this here
and this here is the same--

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:15.460 align:middle line:84%
it's two different
representation

00:27:15.460 --> 00:27:17.420 align:middle line:90%
of the same rational number.

00:27:17.420 --> 00:27:26.460 align:middle line:84%
So we have that m1/n1
is equal to m2/n2.

00:27:26.460 --> 00:27:31.900 align:middle line:84%
So remember that this just meant
that when you multiply over

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:35.140 align:middle line:84%
here, like that, then you
get the same integers-- so

00:27:35.140 --> 00:27:40.040 align:middle line:90%
this here, n2, plus m2 times n1.

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:43.500 align:middle line:84%
That's what it meant, that
these here were the same.

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:48.620 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, you have the
two rational numbers here.

00:27:48.620 --> 00:27:49.620 align:middle line:90%
This is one.

00:27:49.620 --> 00:27:54.820 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to that
p2 divided by q2.

00:27:54.820 --> 00:27:57.900 align:middle line:84%
This just meant that
when you multiply over,

00:27:57.900 --> 00:28:03.750 align:middle line:90%
p1 q2 is equal to p2 q1.

00:28:03.750 --> 00:28:07.480 align:middle line:90%


00:28:07.480 --> 00:28:12.000 align:middle line:84%
So this just meant that
these two represent

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.780 align:middle line:90%
the same rational number.

00:28:13.780 --> 00:28:17.560 align:middle line:84%
These two represent the
same rational number.

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:21.920 align:middle line:84%
And now what we need to prove
is that the product here

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:26.480 align:middle line:84%
is independent of
these representations.

00:28:26.480 --> 00:28:30.160 align:middle line:90%
So the product here is--

00:28:30.160 --> 00:28:33.420 align:middle line:84%
so we need to prove the
products of the first--

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:36.520 align:middle line:90%


00:28:36.520 --> 00:28:40.320 align:middle line:84%
this product here,
this product here,

00:28:40.320 --> 00:28:50.040 align:middle line:84%
this is just m1 times p1
divided by n1 times q1.

00:28:50.040 --> 00:28:59.960 align:middle line:84%
And this is what we want to
show, that this thing here

00:28:59.960 --> 00:29:03.720 align:middle line:84%
is the same if we took
this other representation

00:29:03.720 --> 00:29:07.340 align:middle line:84%
and multiply it by the
other reputation of this.

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:15.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is m2 times
p2, m2 times q2.

00:29:15.900 --> 00:29:19.980 align:middle line:84%
That's what we want to prove,
that those two are same.

00:29:19.980 --> 00:29:22.660 align:middle line:90%
And so we need to prove that.

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:35.420 align:middle line:84%
So we need to show
that m1 p1 times

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:40.940 align:middle line:90%
this denominator here into q2--

00:29:40.940 --> 00:29:50.220 align:middle line:84%
we need to prove, need to
show that this thing here

00:29:50.220 --> 00:29:58.920 align:middle line:90%
is equal to m2 p2 n1 q1.

00:29:58.920 --> 00:30:02.420 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to prove.

00:30:02.420 --> 00:30:04.860 align:middle line:90%
But now let's see.

00:30:04.860 --> 00:30:20.640 align:middle line:84%
So we know that if we take
m1 and together with n2,

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:25.620 align:middle line:84%
m1 together with n2,
this is the same as--

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:32.340 align:middle line:84%
so this here is
the same as m2 n1.

00:30:32.340 --> 00:30:35.600 align:middle line:90%
This is what this here say.

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:40.760 align:middle line:84%
And it also says that if you
take p1 together with q2, then

00:30:40.760 --> 00:30:44.120 align:middle line:84%
you may as well write
this thing here.

00:30:44.120 --> 00:30:49.400 align:middle line:90%
So you may as well write p2 q1.

00:30:49.400 --> 00:30:52.400 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is equal to that.

00:30:52.400 --> 00:30:56.360 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
here, you have m2.

00:30:56.360 --> 00:30:57.920 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have n1.

00:30:57.920 --> 00:30:59.440 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have p2.

00:30:59.440 --> 00:31:01.100 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have q1.

00:31:01.100 --> 00:31:03.140 align:middle line:90%
So those two are the same.

00:31:03.140 --> 00:31:07.780 align:middle line:84%
So this proves that this
operation of multiplication

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:10.340 align:middle line:84%
is well defined in
the rational number--

00:31:10.340 --> 00:31:13.940 align:middle line:90%
and similarly for addition.

00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:16.460 align:middle line:84%
The reason, of course,
why I chose multiplication

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:20.160 align:middle line:84%
is that it looks a little
simpler on the blackboard.

00:31:20.160 --> 00:31:22.760 align:middle line:84%
It's a little more messy
if you did addition.

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:27.212 align:middle line:90%
But it's just exactly the same.

00:31:27.212 --> 00:31:27.712 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:27.712 --> 00:31:36.660 align:middle line:90%


00:31:36.660 --> 00:31:40.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is also
supposed to illustrate

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:42.800 align:middle line:90%
how detailed a proof is.

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:46.260 align:middle line:84%
So when we have a
concept like this,

00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:50.280 align:middle line:84%
we want to make sure that
it really makes sense.

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:53.160 align:middle line:84%
And in this case, it makes
sense that it's well defined.

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:56.500 align:middle line:84%
It's independent
under representation.

00:31:56.500 --> 00:31:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And so the proof here, this
here would be the proof.

00:31:59.170 --> 00:32:02.793 align:middle line:90%


00:32:02.793 --> 00:32:03.293 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:03.293 --> 00:32:05.880 align:middle line:90%


00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:08.320 align:middle line:84%
So the takeaway
here at the moment

00:32:08.320 --> 00:32:10.860 align:middle line:90%
is, we're building towards this.

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:12.220 align:middle line:90%
We're understanding a field.

00:32:12.220 --> 00:32:16.200 align:middle line:84%
We want to understand
the real numbers.

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:22.160 align:middle line:84%
But the takeaway at the moment
is that on the rational numbers,

00:32:22.160 --> 00:32:25.400 align:middle line:84%
there is a way of adding
two rational numbers

00:32:25.400 --> 00:32:27.540 align:middle line:84%
and multiplying two
rational numbers.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:31.080 align:middle line:90%
And there's also an ordering.

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:36.740 align:middle line:84%
And so this leads us to
the following definition.

00:32:36.740 --> 00:32:47.680 align:middle line:90%


00:32:47.680 --> 00:32:50.960 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
definition of a field.

00:32:50.960 --> 00:33:05.050 align:middle line:84%
So a field-- and I will use F
here, capital F for a field--

00:33:05.050 --> 00:33:06.070 align:middle line:90%
is the following.

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:12.290 align:middle line:90%


00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:18.750 align:middle line:84%
So it's a set with
two operations.

00:33:18.750 --> 00:33:26.450 align:middle line:90%


00:33:26.450 --> 00:33:31.530 align:middle line:84%
And the operations we are
denoting suggestively by--

00:33:31.530 --> 00:33:34.410 align:middle line:84%
so the two operations
are denoted suggestively

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:49.005 align:middle line:84%
by a plus and a
multiplication, like a dot.

00:33:49.005 --> 00:33:52.150 align:middle line:90%
But this is just abstract.

00:33:52.150 --> 00:33:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So we have a set, and we
have these two operations.

00:33:56.750 --> 00:34:01.470 align:middle line:84%
What property do these two
operations need to have?

00:34:01.470 --> 00:34:05.790 align:middle line:84%
Each of them have
five properties.

00:34:05.790 --> 00:34:08.750 align:middle line:84%
So that means that
there are 10 properties.

00:34:08.750 --> 00:34:12.350 align:middle line:84%
And then there's 11 properties
that chain those two operations

00:34:12.350 --> 00:34:13.110 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:34:13.110 --> 00:34:15.530 align:middle line:90%
So let's start with addition.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:21.170 align:middle line:90%
So properties of addition--

00:34:21.170 --> 00:34:25.909 align:middle line:90%


00:34:25.909 --> 00:34:30.449 align:middle line:84%
so the first property is
that addition make any sense.

00:34:30.449 --> 00:34:35.590 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a
element in the field

00:34:35.590 --> 00:34:40.270 align:middle line:84%
and you take another
element in the field,

00:34:40.270 --> 00:34:44.969 align:middle line:84%
then addition gives
you a third element.

00:34:44.969 --> 00:34:47.230 align:middle line:84%
So when you add
these together, this

00:34:47.230 --> 00:34:51.790 align:middle line:84%
is just a third
element in the field.

00:34:51.790 --> 00:34:54.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is the first
property, that it really

00:34:54.050 --> 00:34:57.730 align:middle line:84%
is an operation that when you
take two elements of the field,

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:01.290 align:middle line:84%
then you get another
element in the field.

00:35:01.290 --> 00:35:03.290 align:middle line:90%
So this is one.

00:35:03.290 --> 00:35:10.450 align:middle line:84%
The second is that if you
add two elements together--

00:35:10.450 --> 00:35:12.830 align:middle line:90%
so x and y are in the field.

00:35:12.830 --> 00:35:15.190 align:middle line:84%
If you add two
elements together,

00:35:15.190 --> 00:35:20.350 align:middle line:84%
then the ordering that
you're adding is irrelevant.

00:35:20.350 --> 00:35:23.390 align:middle line:84%
So this here is the
same as y plus x.

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:28.530 align:middle line:90%


00:35:28.530 --> 00:35:32.410 align:middle line:84%
Then the next one is--
this is sometimes called

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:35.890 align:middle line:84%
abelian or commutative,
this property here.

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:38.890 align:middle line:84%
Then there's a third
property, which

00:35:38.890 --> 00:35:42.810 align:middle line:84%
is that if you add
two elements together

00:35:42.810 --> 00:35:48.770 align:middle line:84%
and then you add a third
element to the sum of these two,

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:52.830 align:middle line:84%
then this here is
the same as that you

00:35:52.830 --> 00:35:58.150 align:middle line:84%
can add the last
two first and then

00:35:58.150 --> 00:36:01.010 align:middle line:84%
add the first one to the
sum of the other two.

00:36:01.010 --> 00:36:17.790 align:middle line:90%


00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:23.670 align:middle line:84%
And so the fourth
property is that there

00:36:23.670 --> 00:36:28.470 align:middle line:84%
is what is sometimes referred
to as a neutral element.

00:36:28.470 --> 00:36:48.190 align:middle line:84%
So there exists an element
that we denote by 0.

00:36:48.190 --> 00:36:52.290 align:middle line:84%
But it's just to make it
kind of easier to understand,

00:36:52.290 --> 00:36:54.330 align:middle line:90%
that we denote by 0.

00:36:54.330 --> 00:37:07.770 align:middle line:84%
And it has the property that
if you take this 0 element

00:37:07.770 --> 00:37:12.650 align:middle line:84%
and you add it to any
other element, then it just

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:15.250 align:middle line:84%
gives you back
that other element.

00:37:15.250 --> 00:37:19.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's kind of neutral
for the operation.

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:24.050 align:middle line:84%
And then there's supposed
to be a fifth property.

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:33.490 align:middle line:84%
And the fifth property is
that for any element x,

00:37:33.490 --> 00:37:40.200 align:middle line:90%
there exist another element.

00:37:40.200 --> 00:37:44.650 align:middle line:90%


00:37:44.650 --> 00:37:49.590 align:middle line:84%
And again, we write this
suggestively by minus x

00:37:49.590 --> 00:37:52.950 align:middle line:84%
with a bracket
around, like this.

00:37:52.950 --> 00:38:04.526 align:middle line:84%
So there is another
element with the property

00:38:04.526 --> 00:38:10.150 align:middle line:84%
that if you take x and you're
adding this other element, then

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:12.750 align:middle line:90%
you get 0.

00:38:12.750 --> 00:38:18.990 align:middle line:84%
So those are the five properties
that addition has to have.

00:38:18.990 --> 00:38:23.810 align:middle line:84%
And then multiplication have
to have five properties also.

00:38:23.810 --> 00:38:29.910 align:middle line:84%
And these are similar to
this with a little twist.

00:38:29.910 --> 00:38:36.190 align:middle line:84%
And so for
multiplication, you need

00:38:36.190 --> 00:38:37.850 align:middle line:84%
to have the
following properties.

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:41.950 align:middle line:90%


00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:44.470 align:middle line:90%
So again, it's five properties.

00:38:44.470 --> 00:38:51.170 align:middle line:84%
The first one is the similar
property to the property 1

00:38:51.170 --> 00:38:55.370 align:middle line:84%
up there, namely that if you
take two elements, x and y,

00:38:55.370 --> 00:39:02.890 align:middle line:84%
in the field, then when
you multiply them together,

00:39:02.890 --> 00:39:06.850 align:middle line:84%
that should give you another
element in the field.

00:39:06.850 --> 00:39:09.090 align:middle line:90%
So that's the first.

00:39:09.090 --> 00:39:16.730 align:middle line:84%
The second one is similar to
2 up there, is that x times y

00:39:16.730 --> 00:39:19.350 align:middle line:90%
should be the same as y times x.

00:39:19.350 --> 00:39:22.170 align:middle line:90%


00:39:22.170 --> 00:39:25.730 align:middle line:84%
So again, that's often
referred to that it

00:39:25.730 --> 00:39:30.530 align:middle line:90%
is abelian or commutative.

00:39:30.530 --> 00:39:40.010 align:middle line:84%
The third property, it's similar
to the third property up there--

00:39:40.010 --> 00:39:43.250 align:middle line:84%
is that if you take
x times y and then

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:46.590 align:middle line:84%
you multiply it by
a third element,

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:50.030 align:middle line:84%
then you could as well
have first multiplied

00:39:50.030 --> 00:39:54.990 align:middle line:84%
the two last elements and then
multiply by the first element,

00:39:54.990 --> 00:39:57.750 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:39:57.750 --> 00:40:05.510 align:middle line:84%
And then the fourth property
is similar to that property 4

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:22.710 align:middle line:84%
up there, is that there exists
an element denoted suggestively

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:30.390 align:middle line:84%
by 1 here, with a property
that 1 times any element

00:40:30.390 --> 00:40:35.790 align:middle line:84%
x just give you back
that element, x.

00:40:35.790 --> 00:40:38.890 align:middle line:84%
And then the fifth is
similar, except there

00:40:38.890 --> 00:40:40.600 align:middle line:90%
is a twist, slight twist.

00:40:40.600 --> 00:40:44.170 align:middle line:90%


00:40:44.170 --> 00:40:49.170 align:middle line:84%
And so the fifth
property is that--

00:40:49.170 --> 00:40:52.450 align:middle line:84%
but it's very similar to
that fifth over there.

00:40:52.450 --> 00:40:54.270 align:middle line:84%
The fifth property
is the following.

00:40:54.270 --> 00:40:57.410 align:middle line:90%


00:40:57.410 --> 00:41:00.050 align:middle line:84%
The fifth property
here is that there

00:41:00.050 --> 00:41:12.170 align:middle line:84%
exists that for any x
in the field except 0--

00:41:12.170 --> 00:41:14.970 align:middle line:90%
you have to disregard 0.

00:41:14.970 --> 00:41:23.940 align:middle line:84%
For any other elements,
there exist an element--

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:27.130 align:middle line:90%


00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:44.270 align:middle line:84%
and, again, suggestively denoted
by 1/x with the property that x

00:41:44.270 --> 00:41:48.790 align:middle line:90%
times 1/x is equal to 1.

00:41:48.790 --> 00:41:49.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:49.290 --> 00:41:55.910 align:middle line:84%
So those are the five properties
for addition, five properties

00:41:55.910 --> 00:41:57.290 align:middle line:90%
for multiplication.

00:41:57.290 --> 00:42:00.950 align:middle line:84%
And you see that the
one for multiplication

00:42:00.950 --> 00:42:03.730 align:middle line:84%
is like a mirror of
the one for addition,

00:42:03.730 --> 00:42:08.150 align:middle line:84%
except the fifth one has
that you have to look away

00:42:08.150 --> 00:42:09.680 align:middle line:90%
from the 0 element.

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:15.650 align:middle line:90%


00:42:15.650 --> 00:42:18.310 align:middle line:90%
And so, again, this is just--

00:42:18.310 --> 00:42:21.710 align:middle line:84%
1 is just that it
is an operation.

00:42:21.710 --> 00:42:25.510 align:middle line:84%
2 is usually called the
abelian property or commutative

00:42:25.510 --> 00:42:26.590 align:middle line:90%
property.

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:29.510 align:middle line:84%
This is called the
associative property.

00:42:29.510 --> 00:42:34.670 align:middle line:84%
This, it's often also referred
to as a neutral element.

00:42:34.670 --> 00:42:40.110 align:middle line:84%
And this here, that
exists this element--

00:42:40.110 --> 00:42:43.090 align:middle line:84%
in this case, minus
x is sometimes

00:42:43.090 --> 00:42:44.520 align:middle line:90%
called the inverse element--

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:47.090 align:middle line:90%


00:42:47.090 --> 00:42:50.130 align:middle line:90%
and likewise for multiplication.

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:54.370 align:middle line:84%
And then there is,
again, an 11th property.

00:42:54.370 --> 00:42:55.890 align:middle line:84%
And that's a
property because you

00:42:55.890 --> 00:42:58.250 align:middle line:84%
see that those-- at
the moment, there's

00:42:58.250 --> 00:43:02.050 align:middle line:84%
basically no interaction
between these two operations.

00:43:02.050 --> 00:43:05.050 align:middle line:84%
The only way that you
see some interaction,

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:10.250 align:middle line:84%
but this is very little, is that
the fifth property over here

00:43:10.250 --> 00:43:13.570 align:middle line:84%
refer to the neutral
element for addition.

00:43:13.570 --> 00:43:17.130 align:middle line:84%
But they don't really chain
the two operations together.

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:20.290 align:middle line:84%
And that is the last property
that is often referred

00:43:20.290 --> 00:43:22.070 align:middle line:90%
to as the distributive law.

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:32.800 align:middle line:84%
So this is an axiom
chaining addition--

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:42.230 align:middle line:84%
write it like this, addition
together with multiplication.

00:43:42.230 --> 00:43:53.390 align:middle line:90%


00:43:53.390 --> 00:44:03.950 align:middle line:84%
And that's if you take x and
you multiply it by y plus z--

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:08.030 align:middle line:84%
you take the sum here, and
then you multiply it by x.

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:11.190 align:middle line:84%
That is supposed to
be the same as where

00:44:11.190 --> 00:44:19.830 align:middle line:84%
you first multiply x with y
and then you multiply x by z.

00:44:19.830 --> 00:44:23.550 align:middle line:84%
So this is often called
the distributive law.

00:44:23.550 --> 00:44:27.390 align:middle line:84%
And that's a law, again, or
axiom that is chaining these two

00:44:27.390 --> 00:44:30.303 align:middle line:90%
operations together.

00:44:30.303 --> 00:44:30.803 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:30.803 --> 00:44:37.610 align:middle line:84%
So now let's try
to see-- so let me

00:44:37.610 --> 00:44:43.130 align:middle line:84%
just establish just one
little property of a field.

00:44:43.130 --> 00:44:55.382 align:middle line:84%
And you see that when we talk
about the axioms for addition,

00:44:55.382 --> 00:44:59.250 align:middle line:84%
I just said that there had
to exist one element that we

00:44:59.250 --> 00:45:02.410 align:middle line:84%
call the 0 element, and it
had to have some property.

00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:04.270 align:middle line:84%
But maybe there
are many elements.

00:45:04.270 --> 00:45:06.080 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
first little theorem.

00:45:06.080 --> 00:45:10.090 align:middle line:90%


00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:18.210 align:middle line:84%
For any field-- I just
write it as capital Field.

00:45:18.210 --> 00:45:20.460 align:middle line:90%
But it's just to--

00:45:20.460 --> 00:45:22.970 align:middle line:90%
but you don't really have to.

00:45:22.970 --> 00:45:37.260 align:middle line:84%
For any field F, there
exist only one zero element.

00:45:37.260 --> 00:45:43.390 align:middle line:90%


00:45:43.390 --> 00:45:44.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:46.750 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to prove this.

00:45:46.750 --> 00:45:54.550 align:middle line:84%
And again, there's all
kind of important concepts

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:55.610 align:middle line:90%
in this class.

00:45:55.610 --> 00:46:02.910 align:middle line:84%
But there's also another thing
that is important to learn.

00:46:02.910 --> 00:46:04.630 align:middle line:84%
And you have to be
a little bit patient

00:46:04.630 --> 00:46:09.510 align:middle line:84%
because it will take you a
little bit of time to learn it--

00:46:09.510 --> 00:46:13.510 align:middle line:84%
is how to write a
mathematical proof.

00:46:13.510 --> 00:46:17.710 align:middle line:84%
And so this here just gives you
just a little bit of idea of it.

00:46:17.710 --> 00:46:23.230 align:middle line:84%
So we want to prove that there
exists only one zero element.

00:46:23.230 --> 00:46:39.070 align:middle line:84%
So assume that O1 and O2
are both zero element.

00:46:39.070 --> 00:46:45.780 align:middle line:90%


00:46:45.780 --> 00:46:54.360 align:middle line:84%
So that it's a zero
element just means

00:46:54.360 --> 00:46:58.200 align:middle line:84%
that if you take O1 and
you add anything to it--

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:00.440 align:middle line:84%
x could be anything
in the field--

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:02.120 align:middle line:90%
then you get x back.

00:47:02.120 --> 00:47:05.080 align:middle line:84%
That is that O1
is a zero element.

00:47:05.080 --> 00:47:08.840 align:middle line:84%
That O2 is a zero element
just means the same thing--

00:47:08.840 --> 00:47:12.986 align:middle line:84%
that if you take anything
in x, then you get x back.

00:47:12.986 --> 00:47:17.520 align:middle line:84%
And now we want to prove
that O1 is equal to O2.

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:21.400 align:middle line:90%
So I just write O1 plus O2.

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:25.800 align:middle line:84%
But now I'm just thinking
about this O2 as my x.

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:30.000 align:middle line:90%
So I'm adding 0 O1 to this x.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:33.780 align:middle line:84%
So I know that I'm just
getting this here back.

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:38.700 align:middle line:90%
Is because O1 is a 0 element.

00:47:38.700 --> 00:47:42.540 align:middle line:84%
But I could do the same
with O2 that I take.

00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:46.380 align:middle line:84%
The ordering I know
already is irrelevant,

00:47:46.380 --> 00:47:49.160 align:middle line:84%
whether it's O1 plus
O2 or O2 plus O1.

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:50.260 align:middle line:90%
That's the same.

00:47:50.260 --> 00:47:54.900 align:middle line:84%
So I can think about
this O1 here as my x.

00:47:54.900 --> 00:47:58.880 align:middle line:90%
And so I'm adding the O2 to it.

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:01.660 align:middle line:84%
But then I know that I'm
getting this here back.

00:48:01.660 --> 00:48:06.120 align:middle line:84%
So this here must
also be equal to O1.

00:48:06.120 --> 00:48:08.210 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
O1 is equal to O2.

00:48:08.210 --> 00:48:11.940 align:middle line:90%


00:48:11.940 --> 00:48:18.900 align:middle line:84%
And of course, in the
notes that are post,

00:48:18.900 --> 00:48:21.290 align:middle line:84%
things are written
slightly more rigorous.

00:48:21.290 --> 00:48:25.540 align:middle line:90%


00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:27.540 align:middle line:84%
There's a little
bit more meat to it.

00:48:27.540 --> 00:48:31.320 align:middle line:84%
Here, I write it a little
bit shorter on the board.

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:33.790 align:middle line:90%
So look also at the notes.

00:48:33.790 --> 00:48:36.500 align:middle line:90%


00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:37.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:39.640 align:middle line:90%


00:48:39.640 --> 00:48:42.300 align:middle line:90%
So now we know what a field is.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:46.360 align:middle line:84%
So a field, again, it has
these two operations, additions

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:47.840 align:middle line:90%
and multiplication.

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:50.780 align:middle line:84%
Each of those operations
have five properties.

00:48:50.780 --> 00:48:53.800 align:middle line:84%
And then there's 11 properties
that chain those two operations

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:55.920 align:middle line:90%
together.

00:48:55.920 --> 00:48:59.470 align:middle line:84%
And so the examples
of a fields is--

00:48:59.470 --> 00:49:04.240 align:middle line:90%


00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:06.390 align:middle line:90%
so we already have an example.

00:49:06.390 --> 00:49:11.560 align:middle line:90%


00:49:11.560 --> 00:49:14.290 align:middle line:84%
So the rational numbers
here is a field.

00:49:14.290 --> 00:49:19.200 align:middle line:90%


00:49:19.200 --> 00:49:26.140 align:middle line:84%
It has these two operations
and with all the 11 properties.

00:49:26.140 --> 00:49:33.700 align:middle line:84%
The natural numbers is not
a field, is not a field.

00:49:33.700 --> 00:49:38.480 align:middle line:84%
It fails even the
most basic thing.

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:41.240 align:middle line:84%
It fails many of the
properties it needs,

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:44.900 align:middle line:84%
but it fails that even the
serial elements is not in it.

00:49:44.900 --> 00:49:52.260 align:middle line:90%


00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:57.150 align:middle line:84%
And the integers here
also is not a field.

00:49:57.150 --> 00:50:04.300 align:middle line:90%


00:50:04.300 --> 00:50:11.160 align:middle line:84%
That is slightly closer to being
a field, but it's still not.

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:13.180 align:middle line:90%
And why is this not a field?

00:50:13.180 --> 00:50:15.320 align:middle line:90%
It's for multiplication, right?

00:50:15.320 --> 00:50:19.860 align:middle line:90%
If you take 2, then write 2.

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:23.460 align:middle line:84%
If you think about 2,
then there should be--

00:50:23.460 --> 00:50:26.580 align:middle line:84%
then the neutral element
for multiplication,

00:50:26.580 --> 00:50:29.080 align:middle line:90%
that's the usual 1.

00:50:29.080 --> 00:50:31.880 align:middle line:84%
But if you take,
say, the element 2,

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:34.620 align:middle line:84%
then there should be an
element like the inverse.

00:50:34.620 --> 00:50:37.920 align:middle line:84%
There should be an element with
the property that if you take 2

00:50:37.920 --> 00:50:43.380 align:middle line:84%
and you multiply with that
element, then you should get 1.

00:50:43.380 --> 00:50:46.060 align:middle line:84%
That should be the inverse
element, 1 over it.

00:50:46.060 --> 00:50:47.580 align:middle line:90%
But this is like a half.

00:50:47.580 --> 00:50:51.860 align:middle line:84%
But you're missing a
half in the integers.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:53.740 align:middle line:84%
So that's why this
here is not a field.

00:50:53.740 --> 00:50:56.480 align:middle line:90%


00:50:56.480 --> 00:50:57.770 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:57.770 --> 00:51:02.200 align:middle line:84%
So the next concept
is-- so, again, we're

00:51:02.200 --> 00:51:06.200 align:middle line:84%
working our way towards
trying to understand

00:51:06.200 --> 00:51:08.720 align:middle line:84%
what property of
the real numbers

00:51:08.720 --> 00:51:13.040 align:middle line:84%
that we need in order to
make the intermediate value

00:51:13.040 --> 00:51:18.560 align:middle line:90%
theorem, the proof regression.

00:51:18.560 --> 00:51:24.600 align:middle line:84%
And so we now know
what a field is.

00:51:24.600 --> 00:51:29.420 align:middle line:90%


00:51:29.420 --> 00:51:34.620 align:middle line:84%
The next few slides, I'll talk
about complete, what that means.

00:51:34.620 --> 00:51:40.440 align:middle line:90%
But we also have this ordering.

00:51:40.440 --> 00:51:43.420 align:middle line:84%
So what does it mean
that a field is ordered?

00:51:43.420 --> 00:51:48.680 align:middle line:84%
So let's start with
an ordered set.

00:51:48.680 --> 00:51:53.940 align:middle line:90%


00:51:53.940 --> 00:51:55.740 align:middle line:90%
So an ordered set--

00:51:55.740 --> 00:52:03.820 align:middle line:84%
so this is a set
denoted by capital S.

00:52:03.820 --> 00:52:07.300 align:middle line:84%
And it has the property that
whenever you have two elements

00:52:07.300 --> 00:52:12.780 align:middle line:84%
in the set, then it should
either be-- and the ordering,

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:17.280 align:middle line:84%
by the way-- so an ordered
set with an ordering--

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:23.120 align:middle line:90%


00:52:23.120 --> 00:52:27.060 align:middle line:84%
and I denote the ordering,
again, suggestively by this.

00:52:27.060 --> 00:52:28.660 align:middle line:84%
I could have used
any other symbol,

00:52:28.660 --> 00:52:31.360 align:middle line:84%
but I'm just suggestively
using this symbol,

00:52:31.360 --> 00:52:35.380 align:middle line:84%
just to make it easier
to remember the property.

00:52:35.380 --> 00:52:39.600 align:middle line:84%
It's like this property
that you know so well.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:46.380 align:middle line:84%
So an ordered set is a
set with an ordering--

00:52:46.380 --> 00:52:52.760 align:middle line:90%


00:52:52.760 --> 00:52:55.400 align:middle line:90%
and, again, denoted by this--

00:52:55.400 --> 00:53:00.600 align:middle line:84%
so that if you take any
two elements in the set,

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:02.830 align:middle line:84%
then one of the three
properties should hold.

00:53:02.830 --> 00:53:07.040 align:middle line:90%


00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:09.140 align:middle line:84%
The following three
properties should hold.

00:53:09.140 --> 00:53:26.060 align:middle line:90%


00:53:26.060 --> 00:53:33.380 align:middle line:84%
One is that-- so either
x should be equal to y.

00:53:33.380 --> 00:53:38.460 align:middle line:84%
2, the other possibility,
is that x is smaller than y.

00:53:38.460 --> 00:53:43.740 align:middle line:90%
Or 3, y is smaller than x.

00:53:43.740 --> 00:53:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So basically, if you
have an ordered set,

00:53:46.560 --> 00:53:48.300 align:middle line:84%
whenever you take
two elements, you

00:53:48.300 --> 00:53:51.180 align:middle line:84%
should be able to compare
these two elements.

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:51.680 align:middle line:90%
Of course.

00:53:51.680 --> 00:53:54.340 align:middle line:84%
These two elements could
be the same elements.

00:53:54.340 --> 00:53:56.020 align:middle line:84%
But if they're not
the same element,

00:53:56.020 --> 00:54:00.340 align:middle line:84%
then one should be
smaller than the other.

00:54:00.340 --> 00:54:01.310 align:middle line:90%
So that's the idea.

00:54:01.310 --> 00:54:03.860 align:middle line:90%


00:54:03.860 --> 00:54:05.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:10.410 align:middle line:84%
And so now the next concept
is an ordered field.

00:54:10.410 --> 00:54:15.480 align:middle line:90%


00:54:15.480 --> 00:54:22.220 align:middle line:84%
So now we have a field,
and we have an ordered set.

00:54:22.220 --> 00:54:46.310 align:middle line:84%
So an ordered field is a field
that is also an ordered set.

00:54:46.310 --> 00:54:51.240 align:middle line:90%


00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:56.720 align:middle line:84%
And then the operations from
the fields and the ordering,

00:54:56.720 --> 00:54:58.860 align:middle line:90%
they should speak to each other.

00:54:58.860 --> 00:55:01.320 align:middle line:84%
So there should be an
interaction between these two

00:55:01.320 --> 00:55:03.200 align:middle line:90%
operations.

00:55:03.200 --> 00:55:17.940 align:middle line:84%
So it has to have-- with
the following properties,

00:55:17.940 --> 00:55:19.679 align:middle line:90%
then if you take--

00:55:19.679 --> 00:55:23.060 align:middle line:90%


00:55:23.060 --> 00:55:24.900 align:middle line:84%
so it's following
two properties,

00:55:24.900 --> 00:55:35.000 align:middle line:84%
that if x is less than y and
you're adding a c to both--

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:45.140 align:middle line:84%
so this here implies that
for any z in the field,

00:55:45.140 --> 00:55:47.800 align:middle line:84%
if you add this
z to both sides--

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:53.620 align:middle line:84%
so x plus z is
less than y plus z.

00:55:53.620 --> 00:55:58.600 align:middle line:84%
So you should be able to
add something to both sides

00:55:58.600 --> 00:56:03.340 align:middle line:84%
and it's still less
than, like that.

00:56:03.340 --> 00:56:06.260 align:middle line:90%


00:56:06.260 --> 00:56:09.620 align:middle line:84%
So this here is,
how do the ordering

00:56:09.620 --> 00:56:11.780 align:middle line:90%
interacts with addition?

00:56:11.780 --> 00:56:15.160 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing is,
how do it act interacts

00:56:15.160 --> 00:56:17.800 align:middle line:90%
with multiplication?

00:56:17.800 --> 00:56:22.440 align:middle line:84%
And there, the property is
that if you take a x that

00:56:22.440 --> 00:56:29.440 align:middle line:90%
is positive and y is positive--

00:56:29.440 --> 00:56:30.480 align:middle line:90%
and the y.

00:56:30.480 --> 00:56:33.920 align:middle line:84%
So you have both x and
y that are positive.

00:56:33.920 --> 00:56:39.480 align:middle line:84%
Then the product of these
two should also be positive.

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:42.960 align:middle line:84%
So then this here, the
product of the two,

00:56:42.960 --> 00:56:44.560 align:middle line:90%
should also be positive.

00:56:44.560 --> 00:56:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And so this is how the ordering
interact with multiplication.

00:56:51.060 --> 00:56:53.720 align:middle line:84%
This is how it
interacts with addition.

00:56:53.720 --> 00:56:56.100 align:middle line:84%
This is how it interacts
with multiplication.

00:56:56.100 --> 00:57:00.590 align:middle line:90%


00:57:00.590 --> 00:57:07.360 align:middle line:84%
And so now-- well, the
first thing you observe

00:57:07.360 --> 00:57:11.840 align:middle line:84%
is that, again, you already
know an example of this.

00:57:11.840 --> 00:57:15.540 align:middle line:90%


00:57:15.540 --> 00:57:24.520 align:middle line:90%
So the rational numbers--

00:57:24.520 --> 00:57:28.230 align:middle line:90%
so Q here is an ordered field.

00:57:28.230 --> 00:57:36.300 align:middle line:90%


00:57:36.300 --> 00:57:39.580 align:middle line:84%
We have already seen
that it is a field,

00:57:39.580 --> 00:57:41.120 align:middle line:90%
has those 11 properties.

00:57:41.120 --> 00:57:43.860 align:middle line:90%
It has addition, multiplication.

00:57:43.860 --> 00:57:45.480 align:middle line:90%
Each of those have 5 property.

00:57:45.480 --> 00:57:49.380 align:middle line:84%
It has the 11 that
chain the two together.

00:57:49.380 --> 00:57:51.940 align:middle line:84%
And we also discussed
the ordering.

00:57:51.940 --> 00:57:53.960 align:middle line:84%
If you take two
rational numbers,

00:57:53.960 --> 00:57:56.240 align:middle line:84%
what does it mean that one
is less than the other?

00:57:56.240 --> 00:57:58.620 align:middle line:84%
It has the property
of an ordering,

00:57:58.620 --> 00:58:02.340 align:middle line:84%
that you can compare any
two elements, any two

00:58:02.340 --> 00:58:05.240 align:middle line:84%
rational numbers, that
either they are the same

00:58:05.240 --> 00:58:08.360 align:middle line:84%
or, if you have two, one
is less than the other.

00:58:08.360 --> 00:58:14.040 align:middle line:90%


00:58:14.040 --> 00:58:18.480 align:middle line:84%
And it also has this,
the additive property.

00:58:18.480 --> 00:58:23.400 align:middle line:84%
And also, the ordering interact
with addition in this way.

00:58:23.400 --> 00:58:26.600 align:middle line:84%
And it interacts with
multiplication in this way.

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:33.280 align:middle line:84%
So the rational number is
indeed an ordered field.

00:58:33.280 --> 00:58:39.360 align:middle line:84%
Now let me just establish
one last property.

00:58:39.360 --> 00:58:42.670 align:middle line:90%
And that is that if I take--

00:58:42.670 --> 00:58:47.880 align:middle line:90%


00:58:47.880 --> 00:58:50.180 align:middle line:84%
well, let me try to prove
a little theorem here.

00:58:50.180 --> 00:58:57.840 align:middle line:90%


00:58:57.840 --> 00:59:03.110 align:middle line:90%
So here's the theorem.

00:59:03.110 --> 00:59:09.420 align:middle line:90%


00:59:09.420 --> 00:59:15.420 align:middle line:84%
So F here is supposed
to be an ordered field.

00:59:15.420 --> 00:59:20.500 align:middle line:90%


00:59:20.500 --> 00:59:25.940 align:middle line:84%
And then we have that
x here is less than y.

00:59:25.940 --> 00:59:34.260 align:middle line:90%
And z here, this is positive.

00:59:34.260 --> 00:59:36.820 align:middle line:90%
So I assume I have this.

00:59:36.820 --> 00:59:40.060 align:middle line:84%
And now I want to show
that-- then I claim that

00:59:40.060 --> 00:59:43.500 align:middle line:84%
from these properties that
our ordered field have,

00:59:43.500 --> 00:59:51.580 align:middle line:84%
I get automatically then x
times c is less than y times c.

00:59:51.580 --> 00:59:55.700 align:middle line:84%
So I claim I get
this property here

00:59:55.700 --> 00:59:59.580 align:middle line:84%
that you know these
properties over here.

00:59:59.580 --> 01:00:01.720 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove that.

01:00:01.720 --> 01:00:19.310 align:middle line:90%


01:00:19.310 --> 01:00:23.550 align:middle line:90%
So what I want to do is--

01:00:23.550 --> 01:00:35.890 align:middle line:84%
so we want to show that x
times z is less than y times z.

01:00:35.890 --> 01:00:38.350 align:middle line:90%
This is what we want to show.

01:00:38.350 --> 01:00:42.090 align:middle line:90%
Now, to say this here--

01:00:42.090 --> 01:00:58.050 align:middle line:84%
this here is equivalent
to showing that--

01:00:58.050 --> 01:01:01.030 align:middle line:90%
so if you take, this you could--

01:01:01.030 --> 01:01:09.890 align:middle line:84%
because this here, if you
add minus y times z-- sorry.

01:01:09.890 --> 01:01:12.570 align:middle line:90%


01:01:12.570 --> 01:01:17.470 align:middle line:84%
If you take this thing
here and to both sides--

01:01:17.470 --> 01:01:26.890 align:middle line:84%
so you take x times z and
then you plus minus x times z,

01:01:26.890 --> 01:01:31.830 align:middle line:90%
then this here is the same as--

01:01:31.830 --> 01:01:35.490 align:middle line:84%
to say that this is less than
that is equivalent to saying

01:01:35.490 --> 01:01:36.430 align:middle line:90%
this thing here.

01:01:36.430 --> 01:01:41.530 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.530 --> 01:01:43.810 align:middle line:90%
Why is that equivalent?

01:01:43.810 --> 01:01:48.530 align:middle line:84%
This is this law here that is
chaining the ordering together

01:01:48.530 --> 01:01:50.970 align:middle line:90%
with addition.

01:01:50.970 --> 01:01:56.310 align:middle line:84%
And this here,
this element here,

01:01:56.310 --> 01:02:00.510 align:middle line:84%
this is just the inverse
element of this product here.

01:02:00.510 --> 01:02:04.679 align:middle line:90%


01:02:04.679 --> 01:02:08.710 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
these two things together,

01:02:08.710 --> 01:02:10.082 align:middle line:90%
that just gives you 0.

01:02:10.082 --> 01:02:19.030 align:middle line:90%


01:02:19.030 --> 01:02:26.950 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, this
here is the same as x.

01:02:26.950 --> 01:02:30.790 align:middle line:90%
So maybe we need to show this.

01:02:30.790 --> 01:02:32.790 align:middle line:84%
But this here, it's
not hard to believe

01:02:32.790 --> 01:02:43.990 align:middle line:84%
that this here is the same
as y times z minus x times z.

01:02:43.990 --> 01:02:46.850 align:middle line:84%
So this here is now--
you can factor out.

01:02:46.850 --> 01:02:51.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is this law, the 11th
law that allow you to factor

01:02:51.910 --> 01:02:53.070 align:middle line:90%
this one out.

01:02:53.070 --> 01:02:58.350 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same
as y minus x times z.

01:02:58.350 --> 01:03:04.450 align:middle line:84%
This was the distributive
law and was the 11th law.

01:03:04.450 --> 01:03:10.170 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that because
y was bigger than x--

01:03:10.170 --> 01:03:20.210 align:middle line:84%
since y here was
bigger than x, this

01:03:20.210 --> 01:03:23.850 align:middle line:84%
is equivalent to saying
that y is bigger than x--

01:03:23.850 --> 01:03:28.450 align:middle line:84%
if you subtract x
on both sides, this

01:03:28.450 --> 01:03:34.090 align:middle line:84%
is equivalent to saying that
y minus x is bigger than 0.

01:03:34.090 --> 01:03:40.520 align:middle line:84%
This is, again, using the
first axiom over here.

01:03:40.520 --> 01:03:44.150 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that
now we have that.

01:03:44.150 --> 01:03:49.810 align:middle line:84%
So we want to prove that
this thing here, this

01:03:49.810 --> 01:03:53.410 align:middle line:84%
here is all equivalent to
proving that this thing here

01:03:53.410 --> 01:03:55.890 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than 0.

01:03:55.890 --> 01:03:58.750 align:middle line:84%
So the claim up there
is equivalent to proving

01:03:58.750 --> 01:04:02.390 align:middle line:84%
that this thing here
is bigger than 0.

01:04:02.390 --> 01:04:07.070 align:middle line:84%
But the difference here, this
difference here is positive.

01:04:07.070 --> 01:04:09.590 align:middle line:90%
This is assumed to be positive.

01:04:09.590 --> 01:04:13.590 align:middle line:84%
The second law that is
chaining the ordering together

01:04:13.590 --> 01:04:17.390 align:middle line:84%
with multiplication say that
if you have something positive

01:04:17.390 --> 01:04:19.330 align:middle line:84%
and you multiply it
by something positive,

01:04:19.330 --> 01:04:21.230 align:middle line:84%
you're getting
something positive.

01:04:21.230 --> 01:04:24.550 align:middle line:84%
And so in order to
prove this here,

01:04:24.550 --> 01:04:27.870 align:middle line:84%
it was the same as proving
that this thing here

01:04:27.870 --> 01:04:29.670 align:middle line:90%
is actually positive.

01:04:29.670 --> 01:04:35.450 align:middle line:84%
And we have now just reduced
it to this second axiom.

01:04:35.450 --> 01:04:35.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:35.950 --> 01:04:38.630 align:middle line:90%


01:04:38.630 --> 01:04:41.710 align:middle line:90%
Is that clear?

01:04:41.710 --> 01:04:43.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:43.010 --> 01:04:44.910 align:middle line:84%
So we go just a
little bit easier

01:04:44.910 --> 01:04:46.130 align:middle line:90%
here in the first lecture.

01:04:46.130 --> 01:04:49.990 align:middle line:84%
This is what I have
for the first lecture.

01:04:49.990 --> 01:04:53.750 align:middle line:84%
But there's a bunch
of different concepts.

01:04:53.750 --> 01:05:00.290 align:middle line:84%
And again, feel free, of
course, to ask any questions.

01:05:00.290 --> 01:05:03.770 align:middle line:84%
On the class, I typically just
linger around for a few minutes

01:05:03.770 --> 01:05:07.290 align:middle line:84%
afterwards if anybody has any
questions after the class.

01:05:07.290 --> 01:05:09.970 align:middle line:84%
And we will also
have office hours.

01:05:09.970 --> 01:05:14.290 align:middle line:84%
I'm just waiting for the
assignment of the TAs.

01:05:14.290 --> 01:05:17.743 align:middle line:84%
So that will be
put all on online.

01:05:17.743 --> 01:05:20.890 align:middle line:90%


01:05:20.890 --> 01:05:21.470 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:05:21.470 --> 01:05:22.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:22.210 --> 01:05:23.510 align:middle line:90%
Let me know how it goes.

01:05:23.510 --> 01:05:26.330 align:middle line:84%
And one more thing is
that this-- again, I

01:05:26.330 --> 01:05:28.370 align:middle line:90%
mentioned before.

01:05:28.370 --> 01:05:31.370 align:middle line:84%
So my experience is that it
takes people a little bit

01:05:31.370 --> 01:05:35.130 align:middle line:84%
of time to get a hang of
this with writing proofs.

01:05:35.130 --> 01:05:39.146 align:middle line:90%
So don't be discouraged.

01:05:39.146 --> 01:05:43.530 align:middle line:84%
A few weeks or months
into the class, things

01:05:43.530 --> 01:05:46.830 align:middle line:84%
will really turn around,
and it will all make sense.

01:05:46.830 --> 01:05:50.130 align:middle line:84%
And then it will
be more fun also.

01:05:50.130 --> 01:05:51.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:51.680 --> 01:05:55.000 align:middle line:90%